k Fair (NDWBF) 2019 is just around the corner. It&rsquo;s not just a major calendar...</span></span></p>','<p style=\"margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in; text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Does reading books make you happier? Well, there is good news for you! <strong>The New Delhi World Book Fair (NDWBF) 2019</strong> is just around the corner. It&rsquo;s not just a major calendar event for the authors and publishers but is equally popular among book readers. As the book industry in India is growing, NDWBF provides a unique trade opportunity for exhibitors along with the ideal platform for promoting titles. So, get ready to indulge into the best of publishing and intellectual worlds. Major publication houses from across the world are likely to exhibit their literary collections at the book fair 2019. </span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in; text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">In 2018, the fair attracted nearly <strong>1,000 exhibitors</strong> from India and over <strong>30 foreign exhibitors</strong>. This year, the fair is going to be even bigger with many literary and publishing programs and conferences lined up for the nine-day event starting from <strong>January 5, 2019, and ending on January 13, 2019</strong>.&nbsp; </span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in; text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong>Organized by National Book Trust</strong>, India in association with Ministry of Human Resource Development, Department of Higher Education, Government of India, Bookfair is the ideal destination for those who just can&rsquo;t get over lively literary activities. Panel discussions, book launches, dialogues, and a lot more awaits you!</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in; text-align:justify\"><em><strong><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">The fair will feature books from all genres, be it Children Books, Sports Books, Fictions, Publications &amp; Journals, Magazines, International Books and even Old Books. Along with Authors Corners, there will be Children Pavilions and International Events Corner. </span></span></strong></em></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in; text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">While the theme of the 2018 edition of the NDWBF was &lsquo;Environment and Climate Change&rsquo;, this time it will be focused on &lsquo;Readers with Special Needs&rsquo;. The emphasis will be on the importance of inclusive learning and reading for children with special needs. There will be an exclusive exhibition of audio books, braille books, and other reading aids for differently-abled and children with ear or eye impairment. You can also find books related to children with ADHD, psychological and behavioral problems at the Theme pavilion to promote the habit of reading among them. </span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in; text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Save the date and book your calendar! Make sure you don&rsquo;t miss out on this fair, which is all about how interesting and empowering the reading can be.</span></span></p>','2019-01-05','2019-01-13','11:00:00','20:00:00','1542796397.jpg','1542796397.jpg',22,'','http://www.newdelhiworldbookfair.gov.in/','http://www.newdelhiworldbookfair.gov.in/','https://www.facebook.com/NewDelhiWorldBookFair','https://twitter.com/ndworldbookfair','','','','https://youtube.com/nbtindia','',0,234,1,1,2,0,1,1,'2018-11-21 17:33:17','2018-11-22 00:37:10'),(36,'TATA Mumbai Marathon 2019 (OVERSEAS RUNNER CRITERIA)','tata-mumbai-marathon-2019',2,0,'<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Mumbai Marathon, which is now sponsored by the TATA group is scheduled to happen on 20 January 2019....</span></span></p>','<p style=\"margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in; text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong>Mumbai Marathon</strong>, which is now sponsored by the TATA group is scheduled to happen on <strong>20 January 2019</strong>. It&rsquo;s time to cheer for a lifetime by running for a good cause. The marathon has its own fundraising platform managed by United Way Mumbai, which has successfully raised Rs 196 crore in association with 512 NGOs over the years. So, if you want to contribute to any social cause, all you need to do is choose an NGO and contribute. Remember, every penny count!</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in; text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">All fitness enthusiasts and amateur runners have a chance to come together and unfold the power of sports. Not just a sporting event, the marathon is also considered as an opportunity for people with varying abilities, caste, creed and social strata coming together for a good cause.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in; text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">All finishers of the full and half marathon will get a medal, and they can download <strong>Timing Certificates of Marathon</strong> Finisher within 21 days of the race day by going on the event website. </span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in; text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\">Participation in the <strong>Open 10K Run</strong> is open to those who are supporting any NGO which has registered for the event under United Way Mumbai. They will have to pay for the <strong>application fee of INR 1400 / USD 45 along with the charity amount</strong>. </span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in; text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong>Tata Mumbai Marathon is happening on</strong> January 20, 2019</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in; text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong>Distance and time cut-off:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><em>Full Marathon: (42.195 KM) </em></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in; text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong>Minimum age eligibility</strong>: 18 years as on race day (Born on or before January 19, 2001)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in; text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><em>Half Marathon: (21.097 KM) </em></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in; text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong>Minimum age eligibility</strong>: 18 years as on race day (Born on or before January 19, 2001)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in; text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><em>Open 10K Run: (10 KM)</em></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in; text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong>Minimum age eligibility</strong>: 15 years as on race day (Born on or before January 19, 2004)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in; text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><em>Dream Run: (6.6 KM)</em></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in; text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong>Minimum age eligibility</strong>: 12 years as on race day (Born on or before January 19, 2007)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in; text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><em>Senior Citizen&rsquo;s Run: (4.7 KM)</em></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in; text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong>Minimum age eligibility</strong>: 60 years as on race day (Born on or before January 19, 1959)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in; text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><em>Champions with Disability: (2.1 KM)</em></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in; text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong>Minimum age eligibility</strong>: 12 years as on race day (Born on or before January 19, 2007)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in; text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in; text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong